subSubSection.paragraph:
Both high-crowned and low-crowned tooth morphologies have been identified within our sample, which we consider to be conspecific due to the shared fine pitting on the labial face. It is important to note that several authors (i.e., 
Case 1981
; 
Cappetta 2012
; 
Cappetta & Case 2016
) have erroneously assumed that because the high-crowned dasyatid teeth can be attributed to males, the low-crowned morphology must belong to female individuals. However, depending on the species, both males and females can have lowcrowned teeth, and the males of some species may develop highly cuspidate teeth during the breeding season (
Kajiura & Tricas 1996
).
